\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 81. S. cephallenia} Heldr.,{\i  Fl. Céphal.} 26 (1882). Woody at base; stems up to 50 cm, with linear or linear-lanceolate basal leaves. In robust specimens the flowers usually in rather crowded, 3-flowered cymes, the inflorescence often with long alternate branches spreading at a wide angle; in small specimens the inflorescence reduced to a single, few-flowered group. Petals white. Calyx 9·5-11·5 mm, glandular-hairy. Capsule 6-8 mm; carpophore 3·5-6 mm, hairy. 2n = 24.{\i  Rocks. • S. Albania and W. Greece}. Al Gr.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b a}) Subsp.{\b  cephallenia} : Basal leaves 3-5 mm wide, lanceolate to spathulate, green. Inflorescence usually many-flowered. Carpophore densely hairy. 2n = 24.{\i  Kefallinia}.
\par

\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b b}) Subsp.{\b  epirotica} Melzh., {\i Bot. Jahrb.}{\b  98:} 51 (1877): Basal leaves 1-2 mm wide, linear to lanceolate, yellow-green; inflorescence usually few-flowered. Carpophore slightly hairy. {\i Throughout the range of the species except Kefallinia}.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 {\b S. paeoniensis} Bornm., {\i Mitt. Thür. Bot. Ver. }nov. ser. {\b 36:} 44 (1925), from S.W. Jugoslavia, has oblanceolate-spathulate basal leaves and an eglandular calyx, but otherwise resembles {\b 81}. It may deserve subspecific distinction.
